******
[2] Nakuru
Date: 9 Apr 2019
Source: The Star [edited]
https://www.the-star.co.ke/news/2019-04-09-anthrax-kills-4-more-buffaloes-rhinos-vaccinated/


Anthrax has claimed 4 more buffaloes in Lake Nakuru National Park, raising the total to 14, as buffalo and rhino vaccination began yesterday [8 Apr 2019]. Four white rhinos have been vaccinated, and 63 remaining black rhinos will also receive injections. The park's 15 white rhinos will be vaccinated within 10 days.

Rhinos share the same range with buffaloes, as do giraffes. The park has 5000 buffaloes, while its capacity is only 1000. Plans are underway to relocate healthy animals to other parks.

Ten buffaloes and a waterbuck died of anthrax and anthrax-like symptoms over the weekend in Lake Nakuru Park. Four more deaths were reported yesterday [8 Apr 2019], and samples were sent for testing. Anthrax can also sicken and kill humans, but the park remains open, and people are usually infected only if they touch infected carcasses, experts said. They can also be infected by breathing in spores of the anthrax bacteria.

State Department of Wildlife PS Dr Susan Koech yesterday [8 Apr 2019] said teams are working on the ground to curb the spread. She said that from today they will increase aerial reconnaissance and patrols in the park to spot sick and dead animals and keep the disease from spreading.

Dr Obadiah Njagi, the director of Veterinary Services, yesterday [8 Apr 2019] told the Star that an anthrax outbreak in rhinos was reported in 2017.

Anthrax is a zoonotic disease that infects both animals and humans. He said Nakuru county is a hotspot for anthrax outbreaks, especially the Rongai area. "We have never been able to establish why, but we only relate this to historical incidents. Once an outbreak occurs, the bacteria can stay in the soil for up to 10 years," Njagi said [Yes, but they have to maintain a sufficient number of live spores in the soil to infect a grazing animal, not just keep a microbiologist busy. Survival very much depends on circumstances. - Mod.MHJ]

KWS head of corporate communications Paul Gathitu said precautions were being taken to ensure the remains are not eaten by scavengers. "We followed the protocols on how we burn the carcass and disinfect the site to avoid contamination," he said.

The 1st case of buffalo deaths was reported on 29 Mar 2019, prompting the KWS team to move in immediately. The disease was confirmed after samples were screened at a lab in Nakuru. Gathitu said drought was responsible for some deaths as wind blows the dust containing anthrax spores, which can be inhaled. This kind of infection is the most serious. [Drought would certainly stress the animals, thereby reducing the necessary infectious dose. Pneumonic anthrax does not occur with wildlife. The risk comes from the drought pushing animals to graze in places with some soil moisture where the spores will be in adequate numbers to infect the grazing animals. - Mod.MHJ].

KWS staff have gone for anti-anthrax jabs in Nakuru and have been given protective gear.

Gathitu downplayed congestion as being a major factor in the spread of the disease. "The population is high, but it contributes only a little; it's not the main factor," he said.

The last time the disease spread in the park was in 2015. Gathitu said most buffaloes are not affected. He said the situation is being monitored, and once the rains start, he is optimistic the situation will be under control.

Farmers in Nakuru and its environs have been put on a high alert and urged to vaccinate their livestock. They have been warned that anthrax spores can be spread by the wind. Farmers should avoid handling animals that suddenly get sick and call a veterinary officer. Animals weakened by the drought are susceptible. "People should report seeing dead animals and only eat meat slaughtered in an authorised area where it has been inspected by a vet," Njagi said.

The 1st case was detected on 29 Mar 2019. The team on the ground includes 15 officers, including 3 veterinarians, 4 scientists, and 8 supporting officers.

Residents said the sewer near the park could contribute to spread of the disease in Nakuru Town and environs. "Fencing the sewer around Lake Kanuu will really help curb the disease. It's easy for animals to come into contact with the bacteria because they drink from the sewer," farmer Peter Yatich said.

[Byline: Gilbert Koech & Agatha Ngotho]

