******
[3] Molo
Date 8 Apr 2019
From: Viki Hansen-Landis <viki.hansen-landis@internationalsos.com> [edited]


This post said they suspected the 18-22 people were infected with anthrax from milk, but I can't find much past evidence of milk from infected animals being infectious.

This from WHO, annex 6, section 3: "Animals with anthrax do not usually discharge the infecting organism in their milk before death, although there have been occasional exceptions (see (2) below; sections 3.3.8 & 3.5.2; Annex 5, section 2.7). Secretion of milk would normally be expected to cease with onset of bacteraemia and illness. The organism would normally only gain entry to the milk-secreting glands through breakdown of blood-vessel walls at terminal stages of the disease, long after secretion of milk had stopped (M'Fadyean, 1909). Milk from other healthy animals in the herd/flock poses no risk of carrying anthrax organisms;" https://www.who.int/csr/resources/publications/anthrax_web.pdf.

Most anthrax outbreaks in recent history have been recorded in beef cattle and bison. Anthrax can also occur in dairy cattle. However, the risk of contracting anthrax from milk or dairy products is extremely low; http://www.inspection.gc.ca/animals/terrestrial-animals/diseases/reportable/anthrax/fact-sheet/eng/1375205846604/1375206913111.

--
Viki Hansen-Landis
International SOS
<viki.hansen-landis@internationalsos.com>

[The wildlife outbreak appears to be winding down; vaccination has been initiated, which is worthy and not without problems, and proper ground & aerial surveillance has been initiated, plus proper carcass disposal. The Kenyan Veterinary Services and State Department of Wildlife are to be commended.

Yes, the initial report stated, "More than 22 people from Tegat Village in Molo were admitted at the Nyayo hospital in Elburgon, with residents fearing they may have contracted anthrax after consuming milk from a sick cow. According to Emily Sang, the Nyumba Kumi chairperson of the area, the 22 include the owner of the cow, his wife and 2 children. Elburgon assistant commissioner Naftali Korir says 18 people have been treated and discharged."

This was a fear of infection from the milk, and from the medical response they were treated with oral antibiotics and discharged. The actual risk from consuming milk from a cow sick with anthrax can be contentious, though I doubt if I would volunteer to find out the reality. The onset of this disease in cattle can be sudden. This cow could well have been milked as usual, and then been dead the next morning with yesterday's milk still in the kitchen at breakfast and the cow dead in the yard. Gastroenteric anthrax is rough, and if they were so infected, they would have needed to be hospitalised, not sent home. But it is an honest fear. When I was a veterinary student at Cambridge, one of our teachers was Storey Pugh; he had had an interesting time as a POW with the Germans. But I remember him telling us how he had, when in practice, consumed milk unknowingly at the moment from a cow on the farm that he had just diagnosed with anthrax. He survived, but it was a worrisome 24-36 hours, and he did not recommend that we follow his example. Nor do I. - Mod.MHJ

